.\" quaoar-server.1 : man page for quaoar-server
.\" Written with AI assistance (Claude, Anthropic)
.TH QUAOAR-SERVER 1 "2026-03-17" "Quaoar" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
quaoar-server \- WebSocket-to-Unix-socket bridge for the Quaoar display protocol
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B quaoar-server
.RB [ \-p
.IR port ]
.RB [ \-s
.IR socket_path ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B quaoar-server
is a message bridge that connects applications using the Quaoar display
protocol to a browser-based SVG renderer.
It accepts one WebSocket connection from a browser and multiple Unix socket
connections from applications, routing messages between them.
.PP
Applications send netstring-framed messages over the Unix socket.
The server translates these to WebSocket text frames, prepending the
application ID for routing.
Events from the browser are routed back to the appropriate application.
.PP
The server implements the WebSocket handshake (including SHA-1 and base64)
and frame encoding directly, with no external dependencies.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-p " port"
WebSocket listen port.
Default: 9090.
Binds to localhost only.
.TP
.BI \-s " socket_path"
Unix socket path for application connections.
Default:
.IR /tmp/quaoar\-0 .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B QUAOAR_DISPLAY
Applications use this variable to locate the Unix socket.
If unset, they connect to
.IR /tmp/quaoar\-0 .
.SH PROTOCOL
Messages between applications and the server use djb netstring framing
.RI ( length:data, ).
Each message has a header line with space-delimited fields and an optional
payload after a newline.
.PP
The server prepends the application ID to messages forwarded to the browser
and strips it from messages coming back.
Negative application IDs are reserved for system channels:
.TP
.B \-1 hello \fIsocket_path\fR
Sent to the browser when a WebSocket connection is established.
.TP
.B \-1 disconnect \fIapp_id\fR
Sent to the browser when an application disconnects.
.PP
Messages from the browser with negative application IDs are broadcast to
all connected applications.
.SH DEPLOYMENT
For localhost development, open
.B quaoar-client.html
in a browser and connect to
.BR ws://127.0.0.1:9090 .
.PP
For production, place
.B quaoar-server
behind a reverse proxy (nginx, caddy, haproxy) that handles TLS and
optionally WebSocket compression via permessage-deflate.
.SH EXAMPLES
Start the server with default settings:
.PP
.RS
.nf
quaoar-server
.fi
.RE
.PP
Start on a custom port and socket:
.PP
.RS
.nf
quaoar-server -p 8080 -s /tmp/quaoar-test
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run a client application:
.PP
.RS
.nf
export QUAOAR_DISPLAY=/tmp/quaoar-0
notepad
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR libquaoar (3)
